{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/samyutta-nikaya/SN1/aranna-sutta/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>At Sāvatthī.</p>\n<p>Standing to one side, that deity addressed the Buddha in verse:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>“Living in the wilderness, <br>\npeaceful spiritual practitioners <br>\neat just one meal a day: <br>\nso why is their complexion so clear?” <br>\n<br>\n“They don’t worry about the past, <br>\nnor do they long for the future; <br>\nthey feed on whatever comes that day, <br>\nthat’s why their complexion’s so clear.\n<br>\nBecause they long for the future, <br>\nand worry about the past, <br>\nfools wither away, <br>\nlike a green reed mowed down.”</p>\n</blockquote>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<p><a href=\"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/samyutta-nikaya/SN1/nandana-sutta/\">SN.1.11. Nandana Sutta (“The Garden of Delight”)</a></p>\n</div>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"At Sāvatthī."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Standing to one side, that deity addressed the Buddha in verse:"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"blockquote","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"“Living in the wilderness, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\npeaceful spiritual practitioners "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\neat just one meal a day: "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\nso why is their complexion so clear?” "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","pr